You will need Vim compiled with Ruby support, then build:

% genmake make
% make
% ./install.sh

In the root of the filesystem tree you want to scan, create a .vff file with
1 extension per line, with the letters i or e before them. i for include, e for
exclude. grep_i and grep_e for the grep mode.

For example:

[~/work/project] % cat .vff
ic
ics
icpp
ih
ijava
itxt
ixml
ilua
ipl
ipy
irb
itcl
iawk
ised
ish
ibash
grep_ic
grep_ics
grep_icpp
grep_ih
grep_ijava
grep_itxt
grep_ixml
grep_ilua
grep_ipl
grep_ipy
grep_irb
grep_itcl
grep_iawk
grep_ised
grep_ish
grep_ibash

If you specify only e's, then it'll allow everything except those e'd
extensions.

When you start vim, it will connect to VFFServer, and start it up if it can't.
Then you can hit ^F (find) or ^E (grep) to bring up the dialog. Start typing to
autocomplete.
